SENATE BILL 888
G1, P5 CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT 6lr3476
By: Senators Lam and Ellis
Introduced and read first time: February 6, 2026
Assigned to: Education, Energy, and the Environment
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Election Districts – General Assembly and Representatives in Congress
3 FOR the purpose of clarifying that certain requirements apply only to districts for the
4 election of members of the Senate of Maryland and the House of Delegates;
5 authorizing the General Assembly to grant original jurisdiction to the Supreme
6 Court of Maryland to review the congressional districting of the State; altering
7 districts for the election of Representatives in Congress for certain elections; and
8 generally relating to election districts.
9 BY proposing an amendment to the Maryland Constitution
10 Article III – Legislative Department
11 Section 4
12 BY proposing an addition to the Maryland Constitution
13 Article III – Legislative Department
14 Section 62
15 BY proposing an addition to the Maryland Constitution
16 Article XVIII – Provisions of Limited Duration
17 Section 6
18 BY repealing
19 Article – Election Law
20 Section 8–702 through 8–709
21 Annotated Code of Maryland
22 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
23 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
24 (Three–fifths of all the members elected to each of the two Houses concurring), That it be
25 proposed that the Maryland Constitution read as follows:
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *sb0888*

2 SENATE BILL 888
1 Article III – Legislative Department
2 4.
3 Each legislative district FOR THE ELECTION OF A MEMBER OF THE SENATE AND
4 MEMBERS OF THE HOUSE OF DELEGATES shall consist of adjoining territory, be compact
5 in form, and of substantially equal population. Due regard shall be given to natural
6 boundaries and the boundaries of political subdivisions.
7 62.
8 THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY SHALL HAVE THE POWER TO GRANT ORIGINAL
9 JURISDICTION TO THE SUPREME COURT OF MARYLAND TO REVIEW THE
10 CONGRESSIONAL DISTRICTING OF THE STATE.
11 Article XVIII – Provisions of Limited Duration
12 6.
13 (A) (1) THIS SECTION SHALL APPLY ONLY TO ELECTIONS FOR THE
14 STATE’S REPRESENTATIVES IN CONGRESS THAT ARE HELD AFTER THE STATEWIDE
15 GENERAL ELECTION HELD IN 2026 AND BEFORE THE EFFECTIVE DATE OF
16 LEGISLATION ESTABLISHING DISTRICTS FOR THE ELECTION OF THE STATE’S
17 REPRESENTATIVES IN CONGRESS FOLLOWING THE 2030 DECENNIAL CENSUS.
18 (2) THIS SECTION TEMPORARILY IS PART OF ARTICLE III –
19 LEGISLATIVE DEPARTMENT, SECTION 49 OF THE CONSTITUTION.
20 (3) THIS SECTION SHALL EXPIRE ON THE EFFECTIVE DATE OF
21 LEGISLATION ESTABLISHING DISTRICTS FOR THE ELECTION OF THE STATE’S
22 REPRESENTATIVES IN CONGRESS FOLLOWING THE 2030 DECENNIAL CENSUS.
23 (B) THE STATE IS DIVIDED INTO EIGHT DISTRICTS FOR THE ELECTION OF
24 THE STATE’S REPRESENTATIVES IN CONGRESS.
25 (C) (1) THE DESCRIPTIONS OF CONGRESSIONAL DISTRICTS IN THIS
26 SECTION INCLUDE THE REFERENCES INDICATED.
27 (2) (I) THE REFERENCES TO:
28 1. ELECTION DISTRICTS AND WARDS ARE TO THE
29 GEOGRAPHICAL BOUNDARIES OF THE ELECTION DISTRICTS AND WARDS AS THEY
30 EXISTED ON JANUARY 13, 2026; AND

SENATE BILL 888 3
1 2. PRECINCTS ARE TO THE GEOGRAPHICAL
2 BOUNDARIES OF THE PRECINCTS AS THEY EXISTED ON JANUARY 13, 2026, AND AS
3 REVIEWED AND CORRECTED BY THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF PLANNING.
4 (II) WHERE PRECINCTS ARE SPLIT BETWEEN CONGRESSIONAL
5 DISTRICTS, CENSUS TRACT AND BLOCK NUMBERS, AS INDICATED IN P.L. 94–171
6 DATA OR SHOWN ON THE P.L. 94–171 CENSUS BLOCK MAPS PROVIDED BY THE U.S.
7 BUREAU OF THE CENSUS AND REFERRED TO IN THIS SECTION, ARE USED TO DEFINE
8 THE BOUNDARIES OF CONGRESSIONAL DISTRICTS.
